@node "FAQSMemoryCardSpace" "FAQ: What is the PS1 MemoryCard capacity?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is the PS1 MemoryCard capacity?"}

If we trust some magazins and MemoryCard manuals, then you can store 1 @{b}mega byte@{ub} on a 15
block MemoryCard.@{par}

@{b}This is wrong!@{ub}@{par}

A MemoryCard can hold 1 @{b}mega bit@{ub} or 128KB!@{par}

   1 MegaBit = 1048576 Bit@{par}

   1048576 Bit / 8 = 131072 Byte@{par}

   131072 Byte / 1024 = 128 KiloByte@{par}

One MemoryCard block contains 8KB! We have 15 blocks. The last block contains the directory of the
card and some reserved data!@{par}



@endnode
@node "FAQSRegion" "What is a Region or Productcode?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is a Region or Productcode?"}

Well, each game is developed with special feature of the region. Every one knows that a US game
isn't working on an european Playstation. To make this work every game becomes an unique code for
this region.


   Example:


   BESLES-00463@{par}
   ------------@{par}
   0123456789ab@{par}

   0     The "B" is constant.@{par}
   1     Region of the developer.@{par}
   2     The "S" is constant.@{par}
   3     "L" Licence@{par}
         "C" Computer Sony products only.@{par}
         So 234 on an european sony game results "Sony Computer Europe" or@{par}
         on a licenced game "Sony Licence Europe"@{par}
   4     The Game is only working on Playstations for this region.@{par}
   5     "S" Software@{par}
         "D" Demo (a PSX demo software)@{par}
         "H" Hardware (controller, memory cards, multitaps, light guns)@{par}
   6     Separator, constant, "-"@{par}
   789ab Number of the game (the licence number). Games may have differend@{par}
          numbers for different regions (4).@{par}

A geman developer for example would get BESLUS-12345 as product id for the US version of a game. The
european id of the same game may look like this BESLES-22222.


Save games may contain 8 additional chars to separate types of save games for the same game. Its
correct to save these 8 bytes are the file name.


   "BESLES-22222Records "@{par}
   "BESLES-22222Settings"@{par}

The easiest way to get those IDs is to open the @{"save game patcher" link "Patc"}! You'll find the
ID in the @{"ProductID" link "PatcProd"} Gadget! The first 12 characters represent the complete
product id followed by 8 bytes of file name, if available.

@endnode
