@node "FAQSMemoryDiskDrive" "FAQ: What is a Memory Disk Drive?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is a Memory Disk Drive?"}

A Memory Disk Drive is a commercial 15 block MemoryCard. The special is, that there is a standard
PC diskdrive connected.@{par}

You want to see it right now? @{"Click here" link "/Pictures/MemoryDiskDrive.jpg/Main"}!@{par}

As you can see it looks like an external Amiga disk drive. Just the two LEDs and the two buttons are
unusual. The buttons are used to activate the transfer to and from disk.@{par}

Is this device useful?@{par}

Well, loading and saving takes 1-1,5 minutes. To save one 15 block MemoryCard one HD disk is
required. There is also an old incompatible and slower version that only supports DD disks. The
hardware is very expensive and you should better by 16 MemoryCards insteed of this device.@{par}

Your save games are better stored on Amiga by using MCControl as on disks. I got a broken Memory
Disk Drive very very cheap on an internet auction (EBAY) and fixed it.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSHardUpdate" "FAQ: What hardware changes were made since V1.40?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What hardware changes were made since V1.40?"}

Well, the standard hardware changed a little with MCControl version 1.40, but it's not required to
make the following modifications, MCControl stays full compatible even when using the old hardware.


Why you should change the hardware?


Well, the new hardware version consumes less CPU power during card access and the card reading speed
depents on the speed of the used card.


What is required to modify the old version?


It's just one little wire! A bridge (connection) between Pin 10 and Pin 12 on the Amiga-connector. I
called it @{b}IRQ Bridge@{ub}, because this wire creates a bridge to the IRQ connector of the Amiga
parallel port.


Thats all!

@endnode
@node "FAQSExternalV" "FAQ: What are the external power supply specifications?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What are the external power supply specifications?"}

The external power supply voltage should be about 9V-18V! The exact voltage isn't important because
the LM317 is creating always the correct value by using the resistors.


The power supply should be able to output more than 200mA! The output of a playstation itself isn't
more than 100mA per powerline, but the LM317 circuits are consuming some energy, too! If you are
only using 15 block cards then 100mA should be enough!


@{b}Do not use power supplies with less than 100mA! They may work, but they are producing much heat
and may burn out!@{ub}


If the power supply isn't able to supplie enough power, it may happen, that your card isn't working
or must be read much slower than normal. Timo Hegemann is using a normal NoName card, but when using
a 9V Battery instead of an external power supply the card turns into a very slow card!

@endnode
@node "FAQSDiskPort" "FAQ: What is the Disk Port Hardware?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is the Disk Port Hardware?"}

The @{"disk port hardware" link "HardDisk"} is identicaly to the standard @{"parallel port version" link "HardPara"}. The
only difference is that the reader is connected to the disk port and not to the parallel port.

@{MS "The good things:"}

There is no need of an external power supply, because there is a 12V line on the disk port you can
use.


You parallel port stays free!


@{MS "The bad things:"}

The disk access will be shut down, because MCControl is using the hardware! @{b}This problem will be
fixed, soon!@{ub}


The disk port reader causes trouble with Index-line driven disk formats like PC-Disk. These disks
aren't working, when as long the card reader is connected! It's possible to avoid this by
disconnecting the /WProt line (pin 14) off your disk port connector. This makes your reader 100%
disk drive compatible. The only side effect is, that you may (depending on memory card) loose the
multi page support.

@endnode
@node "FAQSDiskPortNW" "FAQ: Why my Diskport-Reader isn't working?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Why my Diskport-Reader isn't working?"}

Well, its not possible to make a proper diagnose from a distance, but if your reader supports the
required voltages and all lines are connected right and without cross connections, then your problem
seems to be the Konfiguration.@{par}

Each slot of your reader is handled like a disk drive. Normaly there is already one diskdrive, so
slot1 (df0:) is already in use and the first external drive is DF1: (Slot2)! On bigger Amigas the
first external Drive is DF2 (Slot3), because DF1 is locked for internal usage.@{par}

A500, A600, A1200: Your first external Drive is DF1:@{par}
A1000, A2000, A3000, A4000: Your first external Drive is DF2:@{par}

Use the following Shell/CLI commands to setup the disk port reader: x means the drive number of your
card reader. (1 for df1, 2 for df2, ...)@{par}

SetENV MCCSlotOffset x@{par}
copy env:MCCSlotOffset to ENVARC:@{par}

@endnode
